Interview Questions
1. What are access modifiers in Java, what are their types, and what is their purpose?
-->Access modifiers define visibility (who can access a class, method, variable, or constructor).
    👉 Types:
    public → accessible everywhere
    protected → within package + subclasses
    default (no modifier) → within same package
    private → within same class only
    
    👉 Purpose:
    Control access
    Achieve encapsulation
    Improve security and maintainability



2. Which access modifiers are allowed for top-level classes, and why can't a top-level class be protected or
private?
-->👉 Allowed:
      
      public
      default (no modifier)
      
      ❌ Not allowed:
      
      private
      protected
      
      👉 Reason:
      
      Top-level classes are not members of another class
      private and protected are meant for members (inside classes)
      A top-level class must be accessible either:
      within package (default)
      everywhere (public)



3. What does the public modifier mean for a class or interface, and how does it affect accessibility across packages?
-->A public class or interface is accessible from anywhere, including other packages.
        It can be imported and used by any other class in any package.    
        Example: 

        package com.example;        
        public class MyClass {
            public void display() {
                System.out.println("Hello");
            }
        }
        
        ➡ This class can be accessed from any package using import.


4. What does it mean for a class to have default (package-private) access, and can such a class be accessed
from another package?
-->When no modifier is specified, it is default (package-private).
        Accessible only within the same package.
        Cannot be accessed from another package, even using import.
        
        Example:
        
        class MyClass {
            void show() {
                System.out.println("Default access");
            }
        }
        
        ➡ Accessible only inside the same package


5. How do access modifiers apply to constructors, and what impact do they have on object creation and
inheritance?
-->Constructors can have all access modifiers:
        
        public constructor → Object can be created from anywhere.
        protected constructor → Accessible within package + subclasses (even in other packages).
        default constructor → Accessible only within same package.
        private constructor → Cannot create object outside the class.
        
        Impact:
        Controls object creation
        Used in design patterns like Singleton
        Affects inheritance:
        If constructor is private → class cannot be extended outside


6. How do access modifiers support encapsulation and data hiding in Java?
-->Encapsulation = wrapping data + methods
        Achieved using private variables + public getters/setters
        
        Example:
        
        class Student {
            private int marks;   // hidden data
        
            public void setMarks(int marks) {
                this.marks = marks;
            }
        
            public int getMarks() {
                return marks;
            }
        }
        
        ➡ Benefits:
        
        Protects data from unauthorized access
        Controls how data is modified
        Improves security and maintainability



7. How do access modifiers differ between class level and member level?
-->Class Level:

    Only public and default allowed
    Cannot use private or protected
    
    Member Level (variables, methods, constructors):
    
    All modifiers allowed:
    public
    protected
    default
    private
    
    Key Point:
    
    Class = controls visibility of class
    Members = control visibility inside and outside class



8. Can we declare a private constructor inside an abstract class? Or can a class be both abstract and final at
the same time?
-->(a) Private constructor in abstract class

        Yes, you can declare a private constructor in an abstract class, but:
        
        Abstract classes cannot be instantiated anyway
        Private constructor restricts subclassing
        
        Example:
        
        abstract class Test {
            private Test() {
                System.out.println("Constructor");
            }
        }
        
        ➡ Not useful in most real scenarios because:
        
        Subclasses cannot access the constructor → cannot extend
        (b) Can a class be both abstract and final?
        
        ❌ No, not possible
        
        Reason:
        
        abstract → must be extended
        final → cannot be extended
        
        ➡ These are contradictory, so Java does not allow it.
